#doc (Page) "About Me" =>

I finished my doctorate in Computer Science at [PUC-Rio](http://www.inf.puc-rio.br) in 2010.
My research spans formal methods, theorem proving, type theory, computational linguistics, and knowledge representation. I am currently Director of CSLib (Computer Science Library in Lean) at [Renaissance Philanthropy](https://www.renaissancephilanthropy.org), a global open-source initiative funded by Amazon and Google, and a participant in DARPA's ExpMath programme on AI-assisted mathematical formalization.

My PhD thesis developed proof-theoretic systems for description logics, and I have extensive experience with interactive theorem provers (Lean and PVS) and SMT solvers (Z3). I also created [OpenWordnet-PT](https://github.com/arademaker/wordnet-br/), the reference wordnet for Portuguese, and contributed to Universal Dependencies, DELPH-IN, and several other international NLP initiatives. I have over 110 academic publications, 3 US patents, and 18 years of university teaching experience.

I finished my doctorate in Computer Science at [PUC-Rio](http://www.inf.puc-rio.br) in 2010. During my Ph.D., I made two international fellowships at Microsoft Research and SRI International. At MSR, in 2008, I worked with the [Z3 SMT Solver](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Z3_Theorem_Prover) team (Leonardo de Moura and Nikolaj Bjørner). At [SRI International](http://www.sri.com/), in 2009, I worked under the supervision of Natarajan Shankar. My thesis proposed new deduction systems for description logics under the supervision of Edward Hermann Haeusler, published by Springer as [A Proof Theory for Description Logics](https://www.amazon.com/Theory-Description-SpringerBriefs-Computer-Science-ebook/dp/B00A9YGJR0).

